1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 e5 7. d3 Nc6 8. Rb1
a5 {This is Black's top choice. By preventing b2-b4, Black invites White to go
a2-a3 because b2-b4 will yield Black control over the a-file. On the downside,
it weakens b5 and allows White to play Nc3-b5 in various cases.} 9. b3 {
A flexible continuation. White prepares finachetto and overprotects his pawn-c4
- this might be important for pushing d3-d4 in the long run.} ({The most
common alternative is} 9. a3 {, but then Black can choose between few
interesting possibilities, such as} Nd4 $5 10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 c6 12. b5 Bg4 {
with active counterplay.}) 9... Re8 {As usual, by playing this move Black
signals that he wants to force simplifications by means of ...e5-e4.} (9... Be6
{has no independent value as after} 10. Bb2 {Black has nothing better than} h6
{, transposing to 9...h6}) ({In the event of} 9... Nd4 {White can claim the
main drawback of ...a7-a5 with} 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Nb5 $1 Ne8 ({Worse is} 11...
Ng4 $6 12. h3 c6 {Oparin,G - Popovic,D Chess.com INT 2017 Now the simple} 13.
hxg4 cxb5 14. cxb5 $16 {would have offered White huge positional advantage.})
12. Bb2 {Forcing Black to play c7-c5 that yields outpost for White's knight.}
c5 13. e3 dxe3 14. fxe3 $14 {White's pieces are much more active and d6 is
weak.}) ({The artificial attempt to build a pawn centre by means of c7-c6 and
d6-d5 with} 9... Ne7 {, as in Yahya,H - Guevara,M Moscow 1994 runs into} 10.
Bb2 $146 c6 11. h3 Re8 12. e4 $14 {, and e7 turns clearly misplaced.}) ({
The most ambitious try is} 9... Nh5 {Black goes all in! The knight is
definitely misplaced, but it can support further ...f7-f5-f4.} 10. e4 f5 11.
Bg5 Nf6 {This position was seen in Elfving,J - Benovic,P ICCF email 2005} ({
After} 11... Qd7 $6 12. exf5 gxf5 13. Nh4 Nf6 14. f4 $16 {Black suffers from
poor piece coordination and weak f5-pawn.}) {Here my new natural idea is} 12.
Qd2 $146 {White maintains a pin by preventing ...h7-h6.} fxe4 13. dxe4 Bg4 14.
Nb5 $1 {Eliminating Black's only active idea with ...Nc6-d4. Of course, e4 is
untouchable in view of Qd5+.} Qd7 15. Kh1 $1 {A decent prophylactic move.
White vacates g1 for the knight's retreat.} Kh8 16. Ng1 $14 {Black has no
compensation for his space issues.}) 10. Bb2 h6 {This thematic move can be
played in different redactions. Black secures e6 for his light-squared bishop.}
(10... e4 {is the most straightforward attempt to solve the issues.} 11. Ne1 $5
$146 {The most ambitious response. White is interested in maintaining the
tension.} ({Instead, after} 11. dxe4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Rxe4 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 {the
position becomes rather simplistic and White can only pretend to claim a tiny
advantage.}) 11... e3 ({Equally possible is} 11... exd3 12. Nxd3 Bf5 13. Qd2
Ne4 {Black lacks space, so it definitely makes sense for him to invite
simplifications.} 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 Rxe4 16. Nf4 $14 {White's knight
reaches d5, which will be a long-term suffering for Black.}) 12. fxe3 Ng4 13.
Nd5 {An important move that allows White to stabilize the situation on the
kingside.} Bxb2 14. Rxb2 Nxe3 15. Nxe3 Rxe3 16. Nc2 Re8 17. Qd2 $14 {White has
a definite advantage due to strong g2-bishop and decent prospects along the
f-file.}) (10... Bd7 {, as in Vilela de Acuna,J - Lechtynsky,J Tallinn 1979
hardly provides Black any active counterplay and it can be well met by} 11. h3
$146 Qc8 12. Kh2 {it is rather unclear what Black's queen is doing on c8} Nd4
13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Nb5 $1 $14 {Whte claims drawbacks of ...a7-a5. Black will
have to confess his strong light-squared bishop.}) 11. h3 $1 {A decent
prophylactic move. White is planning to play e2-e4, so it makes sense to
eliminate ...Bc8-g4 ideas.} Be6 12. e4 {Eliminating any ideas with ...d6-d5
and securing d5 for the knight.} Nd7 {Black moves his knight towards c5 and
unblocks the f-pawn.} 13. Bc1 $5 $146 {A surprising idea. White relocates his
bishop to e3 to properly prepare ..d3-d4.} ({Weaker is} 13. Qd2 Nc5 14. Nd5 Nb4
$1 {Black had excellent play in Yu,Y -Yakubboev,N Chess.com INT 2023}) ({
White didn't achieve much also after} 13. Nb5 Nc5 14. d4 exd4 15. Nfxd4 Bd7 {
Black had counterplay against e4 in Morozevich,A - Tomashevsky,E Tromsoe 2013})
13... Nc5 ({In the event of} 13... f5 14. Nh4 $1 fxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxh3 (15... g5
16. Nf5 $14) 16. Bxg6 Rf8 17. Re1 $14 {White is better due to control over the
light squares.}) 14. Be3 {Both sides played the most natural move and now
Black is invited to show his cards.} f5 ({After} 14... Qd7 15. Kh2 Rf8 {
White manages to take the upper hand in the centre by means of} 16. Qd2 Kh7 17.
d4 exd4 18. Nxd4 $14) 15. exf5 Bxf5 {This is better than 15...gxf5?! 16.d4} 16.
Ne1 $1 {This calm move seems the most promising.} ({The more forcing
alternative is} 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. Nh4 Qxd3 {Of course, not 17...Bxd3? 18.Bd5!}
18. g4 Qxc3 19. gxf5 {provides White interesting play on the light squares,
but after} Ne7 $1 {Black has good chances for neutralizing the opponent's
initiative.}) 16... Nd4 17. Na4 $1 {A powerful resource. White manages to
neutralize the active knights of opponent.} Nxa4 {The most challenging -
White's pawn structure is somewhat damaged now.} ({After} 17... c6 18. Nxc5
dxc5 19. g4 Be6 20. Be4 $14 {White has a slight but stable positional
advantage due to strong e4-bishop.}) 18. bxa4 Rb8 19. Bxd4 {Both Black's
knights are off the board - it is White's certain achievement!} exd4 20. Bxb7
Bxh3 21. Ng2 {In this unbalanced position White has the more pleasant play due
to control over the light squares.} *

