1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 e5 7. d3 Nc6 8. Rb1
a5 9. b3 h6 {This is Black's top choice by far. It is a multi-tasking move:
Black not only secures e6 for his bishop, but also declares his intent to
start expansion on the kingside with ...g6-g5,f7-f5 and so on.} 10. h3 $5 {
A flexible response that was only seen in a couple of high-level games so far.
White leaves his queen's bishop on its diagonal and invites his opponent to
show his cards. Also, in many cases, Black wouldn't be able to exchange the
g2-bishop with ...Bh3.} Be6 {The most consistent. This move has been played in
all the games so far.} ({I've also examined} 10... Nh7 $146 11. Bb2 g5 ({
Premature is} 11... f5 $6 12. Nh4 $1 Ne7 13. Nd5 $16 {g6 turns too weak.}) 12.
d4 $1 {White takes the opportunity of opening the central file before ...f7-f5.
} f5 ({In case of} 12... exd4 13. Nb5 Bf5 14. Nfxd4 $1 Bxb1 15. Qxb1 $36 {
the powerful bishops and full control over the light squares provide White
more than sufficient compensation for an exchange.}) 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Qd5+ $1
{White uses poor h7 to interrupt the opponent's piece coordination.} Kh8 15.
Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Nd5 Rd7 17. e4 $14 {Neutralizing the activity of White's pieces
isn't gonna be an easy task.}) ({The attempt to radically change the character
of play with} 10... d5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 {is risky because Black's centralized
queen is gonna be vulnerable after} 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Bb2 Qd6 14. Nd2 $14 {
In this complex middlegame a-la reversed Sicilian White's chances are
preferable due to more harmonious piece coordination.}) 11. e4 {White
stabilizes the situation in the centre and eliminates any counterplay with
...d6--d5 or e5-e4.} Nh7 {This move is aimed to diminish White's control of d4
with ...Nh7-g5. Also, Black wants to play f7-f5 at the proper moment.} ({
The other knight's move is} 11... Nd7 {Bruzon Batista,L - Sanal,V Berlin 2015 ,
and it can also be met with} 12. Be3 $1 $146 f5 13. exf5 gxf5 ({After} 13...
Bxf5 14. g4 Be6 15. d4 $16 {White is much better due to strong g2-bishop and
superior pawn structure.}) 14. d4 f4 15. d5 $1 {The most energetic.} fxe3 16.
dxe6 $14 {White's fianchettoed bishop prevails.}) ({Too passive is} 11... Kh7
$6 12. Be3 Nd7 13. d4 {Black had no compensation for his structural drawbacks
in Bruzon Batista,L - Supi,L chess24.com INT 2020}) 12. Be3 $1 $146 {White is
now ready to take the upper hand in the centre with d3-d4.} ({Weaker is} 12.
Bb2 Ng5 13. Nxg5 hxg5 {Black was fine in Abramovic,B - Deac,B Arad 2014}) 12...
Nd4 ({The alternative} 12... Ng5 13. Nxg5 hxg5 14. Qd2 {yields White an
important tempo in view of hanging g5-pawn A likely continuation is} g4 15.
hxg4 Bxg4 16. f4 $14 {White's forces are much better mobilized for the
upcoming struggle on the kingside.}) 13. Kh2 $1 {A strong prophylactic move.
Black has to do with exchange on d4 from now.} ({Weaker is} 13. Bxd4 exd4 14.
Ne2 Ng5 $1 {, forcing favorable complications.}) 13... c6 (13... Nxf3+ {
is a clear concession because centralized knight is Black's most active piece.}
14. Qxf3 c6 15. Qe2 f5 {This is practically the only way to involve the
kingside pieces.} 16. exf5 gxf5 17. f4 $14 {White puts strong pressure on f5 an
e5.}) 14. Bxd4 exd4 15. Ne2 {There is no comfortable way of covering d4.} Qb6
16. a3 {White eliminates any ideas with ...a5-a4 and even shows his intention
to push b3-b4 at some point.} Rfe8 17. Nf4 Bd7 18. h4 $1 {White is interested
in exchanging one of the opponent's bishops.} Nf6 19. Bh3 Bxh3 20. Kxh3 $14 {
White has the superior pawn structure and Black's bishop is passive.} *

