1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 e5 7. d3 Nc6 8. Rb1
h6 {This move is by far the most popular among Black's minor options (
regarding that 8...a5 can be considered as the absolute mainline) . As usual,
this move illustrates Black's intention to place the light-squared bishop on e6
and some when pushing g6-g5. The other merit is avoiding a pinning move
..Bc1-g5.} 9. b4 {There is no reason for delaying this ambitious advance.} Be6
({The other natural possibilities are:} 9... a6 10. Nd2 ({The most common
alternative is} 10. a4 Be6 11. b5 axb5 12. axb5 Ne7 {, but control over a-file,
seems to provide Black with some extra counter-attacking abilities. This
position was tested in hundreds of high-level games, and the results are
satisfactory for a second player.}) 10... Ne7 (10... Be6 {tranposes to 9...Be6}
) 11. a4 c6 {This position occurred in Lafuente,P - Fiorito,F Buenos Aires 2001
In my opinion, White could have claimed superiority by means of} 12. a5 $1 $146
Be6 13. Ba3 Re8 14. e4 d5 15. Qc2 $14) ({Too artificial is} 9... Nh7 10. b5 Ne7
{Black is fully focused on developing his queenside play with f7-f5, g6-g5,
e.t.c, but it diminishes his control of d4, so} 11. d4 $1 {looks very
promising for White. A likely continuation is} f5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Ba3 {
Black got under strong pressure along a3-f8 diagonal in Markov,J - Pospelov,E
Budapest 1991}) 10. Nd2 {I like this flexible move. The positional threat of
11.b5 is stronger now because vulnerability of b7-pawn. Also, this moves order
allows White to host his knight on d5 in many cases.} ({Another common
continuation is} 10. b5 Ne7 11. Nd2 Qc8 {Black covers b7 and intents to play
...Bh3} 12. Re1 Bh3 13. Bh1 Ng4 {The engines prefer White's chances here, but
it looks like Black has decent practical counter-chances on the kingside.})
10... Qc8 (10... Qd7 {is equally common as 10...Qc8. Black connects his rooks,
but it makes the b7-pawn weaker than text.} 11. Nd5 {In such positions Black
usually prefers to have his king's knights either on e7 because of ..Nxf6+
threat.} Nh5 ({Too passive is} 11... Ne8 12. b5 Nd8 {Foisor,O - Markowski,T
Biel 1997 Here the simple} 13. e4 $1 c6 14. Ne3 $14 {, followed by f2-f4 would
have claimed Black's main drawback - the poor d8-knight has no prospects.}) ({
Even worse is} 11... Bh3 $6 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Ne4 Bg7 14. Bxh6 $1 {Black had
no compensation for the pawn in Berkvens,J - Zhigalko,A Hengelo 2001}) 12. b5
Nd8 {A sad necessity. Black needs to take care of b7-pawn.} 13. Qa4 $1 {
A powerful manoevre. White transfers his queen to a5 to insist pressure on the
opponent's pawns.} f5 14. Qa5 c6 ({After} 14... Rf7 $2 15. b6 cxb6 16. Nxb6 Qc7
17. Qa4 $18 {Black's queenside was destroyed in Foisor,O - Menoni,V
Montecatini Terme 1994}) 15. bxc6 (15. Nb6 Qc7 {is less clear.}) 15... bxc6 16.
Nc7 {By exchanging e6-bishop White heavily limits the opponent's attacking
potential.} Rc8 17. Nxe6 Nxe6 18. Ba3 $14 {Black's pawn are vulnerable.}) ({
The attempt to neutralize White's strong bishop with} 10... d5 11. b5 Ne7 {
is rather risky because Black's pieces are not fully mobilized for such
confrontation in centre. For instance,} 12. Ba3 Re8 13. Qb3 {White insists
pressure on d5 and connects his rooks.} dxc4 14. Nxc4 Nfd5 {This position
occurred in Musaev,E-Agaragimov,D Baku 2001 After the simple} 15. Bb2 $146 Nxc3
16. Qxc3 $36 {Black would have faced serious problems with defending e5 and b7.
}) (10... a6 {again can be well met by} 11. Nd5 Kh7 ({After} 11... Rb8 12. Bb2
Qd7 13. f4 Bh3 {, as in Vaganian,R - Gallagher,J Pula 1997 White manages to
seize the initiative on the kingside by means of} 14. Bxh3 $146 Qxh3 15. e4 $1
{, and then Black has nothing better than accepting the pawn:} Nxd5 16. cxd5
Nxb4 17. Qb3 a5 18. fxe5 dxe5 19. Nc4 $16 {Black is positionally busted, and
it is only a matter of time before he will lose an extra pawn.}) 12. a4 {
Black is far from making counterplay on the kingside, so White has time for
his traditional extension.} Qd7 13. b5 axb5 14. axb5 Nd8 {The d8-knight
interrupt coordination of Black's pieces again.} 15. b6 {it is a sign that
White should act aggressively!} c6 16. Nc7 Rb8 {We have been following
Kramnik,V - Piket,J Amsterdam 1993 My new natural idea here is} 17. Ba3 $146
Bh3 18. Bxh3 Qxh3 19. f3 {A calm move. It turns out that Black's
counter-attacking abilities are limited.} Qd7 20. Ne4 $14 {White's pieces are
much more active, and d6 is a cause of worries.}) 11. Nd5 {From now ..Ne7+
with a fork is in the air, so Black should be careful.} Bh3 ({After} 11... Nh7
12. b5 Bxd5 13. Bxd5 Ne7 14. Bg2 $14 {White's unopposite finachettoed bishop
secures a clear positional advantage.}) 12. b5 {The most straightforward.
Black's next few moves are forced. Of course, 12.Bxh3 Qxh3 13.Nxc7? Ng4 is
very bad for White.} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nxd5 {This was Ninov,D - Stojanovic,D
Obrenovac 2013 Now I suggest the following new approach:} 14. bxc6 $146 Nb6 15.
c5 $1 {White manages to damage the opponent's pawn chain.} dxc5 16. Ba3 bxc6
17. Bxc5 Rd8 18. Qc2 $14 {Black's extra pawn has a symbolic value - both his
c-pawns are very weak, and White's forces are much better mobilized.} *

