1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 e5 7. d3 Nc6 8. Rb1
Re8 {This move often means that Black isn't planning to develop an attack with
f7-f5, but builds his counterplay on ...e5-e4 push.} 9. b4 (9. e4 $5 {is
another interesting possibility, but I would like to stick with consistent text
continuation.}) 9... e4 {Black is aiming to simplify the matters and activate
his dark-squared bishop.} (9... a6 {can be well met by} 10. Nd2 $1 {White
strengthens d5 and makes ..c3-d5 possible in various cases.} ({Somewhat
premature is} 10. a4 e4 $1 11. dxe4 Nxe4 {Black obtains a better redaction or
our main line because White's setup is overextended here.}) 10... Ne7 ({
After} 10... Be6 11. Nd5 Qd7 12. a4 $14 {Black has no proper counter-play and
his queen is tied with defending c7.}) 11. a4 c6 {We have been following the
game Iniyan,P - Sparenberg,E Hoogeveen 2018 Here I suggest the following
concept:} 12. a5 $1 $146 {White grabs lots of space and secures b6 for his
knight.} d5 13. Na4 Nf5 14. Bb2 $14 {White's superior piece coordination and
control over key squares c5 and b6 overweight opponent's pawn centre.}) ({
The other active try is} 9... Nd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Nb5 Ng4 {, as in
Stanev,V-Klundt,K Ybbs 1968 Now I mostly like} 12. a4 $146 c6 13. Na3 {White
is ready to extend his initiative on the queenside by means of b4-b5, a4-a5,
e.t.c} h5 14. Nc2 h4 {At his turn, Black is trying to put pressure on White's
king.} 15. h3 hxg3 ({After} 15... Nf6 16. Bg5 hxg3 17. fxg3 $36 {White takes
over initiative because of dangerous pin.}) 16. fxg3 {The simplest. Instead,
16.hxg4 xg4 provides Black compensation for the piece.} Ne3 17. Nxe3 dxe3 18.
Bb2 $14 {White has the healthier pawn structure, while the king is safe.}) 10.
dxe4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Rxe4 12. b5 {The most straightforward. White prolongs
diagonal for his bishop.} Na5 ({The more active retreat is} 12... Nd4 {, but
after} 13. Nxd4 Rxd4 14. Qb3 {the centralized rook is in big danger. A likely
continuation is} Be6 15. Bxb7 Rxc4 ({Worse is} 15... Bxc4 $2 16. Qc2 Bd5 {
This was Ivic,V - Matinian,N Chess.com INT 2022} ({Or} 16... Rb8 17. Be3 $18) {
Now the calm} 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 18. Bb2 Rc4 19. Qd2 $18 {would have offered White
a winning position.}) 16. Bxa8 Qxa8 17. Qf3 Bd5 18. Qd3 $16 {The powerful
bishops offer Black only tiny drawing chances - White's material advantage is
too big. Kaufmann,W - Umbach,A Switzerland 2002}) 13. Nd2 {Attacking the rook
and releasing pressure on c4.} Re8 14. Qa4 c5 {A sad necessity. Black's pawn
structure becomes problematic.} 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Nf3 $1 $146 {This innovation
offers White more} ({than} 16. Nb3 Bf5 17. e4 Nxb3 18. exf5 Nd4 {, as in})
16... Be6 ({After} 16... Rxe2 $2 17. Bd2 {Black suffers heavy material losses.}
) ({Insufficient is also} 16... Re4 17. Bg5 Qc7 18. Rfc1 $14 {White's pieces
are much better mobilized, and the Re4 is misplaced again.}) 17. Ng5 $1 {
The most energetic response. White has no reason for covering c4.} Bxc4 18. Bd2
$36 {Activity of all White's pieces and vulnerable a5-knight make Black's
position very dangerous.} *


