1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 e5 7. d3 Nc6 8. Rb1
Nh5 {This somewhat risky move was seen in more than 300 games. Black builds on
fast counterplay on the kingside that is based on expansion with f7-f5, g6-g5
and so on.} 9. b4 f5 {Hardly there is a better option at Black's disposal.} ({
In the event of} 9... Nd4 10. b5 Ne6 ({The immediate} 10... f5 $2 11. Nxd4 exd4
12. Nd5 h6 13. e3 {puts Black on the verge of collapse because White has full
control over the light squares and strong d5-knight is dominant.}) 11. a4 {
White's play is lasting faster.} f5 {This position took place in Niemi,M -
Sousa,R Gaziantep 2008 Here I suggest} 12. e3 $146 {White's queen is keeping
an eye on h5-knight, so Black cannot play g6-g5.} Nf6 13. Ba3 {White declares
his intent to unlock the a3-f8 diagonal with c4-c5} g5 14. a5 g4 {A consistent,
but risky approach.} ({Possibly, Black should opt for a modest} 14... Rb8 {
, but then} 15. Nd5 $14 {White is firmly in a control.}) 15. Nh4 f4 16. exf4
exf4 17. Re1 $16 {Black's attack ends, and he finds himself overextended when
camp has many weaknesses.}) ({Slower is} 9... h6 10. b5 Ne7 11. a4 f5 12. Ba3
$5 {There are a few other attractive options, but I like this move: White
doesn't fear of ghosts and invites favorable complications.} e4 {This is the
only challenging move. Black takes advantage of vulnerable c3-knight.} ({
After} 12... f4 13. c5 $16 {Black was positionally busted in Sychev,K -
Bodnar,N Chess.com INT 2021}) 13. dxe4 Bxc3 14. e5 $1 {An illustrative
situation: White has only one pawn for the piece, but his superior piece
coordination provides more than sufficient compensation. For instance,} Be6 15.
Rc1 $1 Ba5 $2 ({The lesser evil is} 15... Bxe5 16. Nxe5 {, but then White
regains a piece in favorable redaction.}) 16. Nd4 Qd7 17. Nb3 $1 Bb6 18. a5 $18
{with a total collapse.}) 10. b5 Ne7 {This position was seen in no less than
120 games!} (10... Nd4 {transposes to 9...Nd4.}) 11. c5 $5 $146 {I really like
this new ambitious idea. White is aiming to open the game before Black will
consolidate.} d5 {I find this response the most challenging - Black relies on
this strong pawn centre.} ({After} 11... dxc5 12. Ba3 $1 {Black is unable to
cover c5 because} b6 13. Qb3+ Kh8 14. Nxe5 {is nearly lost.}) ({The
prophylactic} 11... Kh8 12. cxd6 cxd6 13. Qb3 {makes it easy for White to
develop his initiative. In particular, 14.Ng5 is a strong threat.} h6 14. Ba3
g5 15. Nd2 $16 {Black struggles to cover all his weak spots.}) 12. e4 $1 {
A well-timed move. Black isn't ready for confrontation in centre.} fxe4 ({
The ambitious} 12... d4 13. Na4 f4 {doesn't really bother White as Black isn't
in time to extend with...g6-g5:} 14. Nb2 $1 {Black's knight is stuck, and
there is no proper way to cover e5.} Be6 15. Nc4 Bxc4 16. dxc4 $16 {White is
firmly in control - next he will transfer his knight to d3 and start pushing
on the queenside. Black lacks any counter-attacking ideas as he is missing the
light-squared bishop.}) 13. dxe4 d4 14. Na4 {The knight is heading on d3 to
block the opponents passer and attack e5.} Qe8 {Black temporarily prevents
..b2 by attacking b5.} ({The only adequate alternative is} 14... Bg4 15. h3 Be6
{, but it fails to interrupt White's plans:} 16. Nb2 $1 Bxa2 17. Ra1 Be6 18.
Nd3 $16 {Black's centre is gonna be destroyed.}) 15. Qb3+ Kh8 16. Nb2 {Black
has to do both with Nd3 and Nc4.} a6 17. a4 axb5 18. axb5 $16 {Most of Black's
pieces are misplaced, and e5 is very weak.} *

