1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 Nc6 {By starting
with this move Black sometimes shows his intention to delay ...e7-e5.} 7. d3
Nh5 {An aggressive plan. Black shows his intention to push the f-pawn and put
White's king under pressure.} 8. Rb1 {White declares his intent to seize lots
of space with b2-b4-b5.} ({The alternative} 8. d4 e5 9. d5 Ne7 {leads to
standard KID struggle.}) 8... a5 ({Riskier is} 8... f5 9. c5 $5 {The most
aggressive. White is trying to convert his superior piece coordination into
something serious.} dxc5 {Black accepts the pawn.} ({In case of} 9... d5 10. d4
Nf6 11. Qc2 Ne4 12. Rd1 $14 {the position resembles Stonewall, when the fast
b2-b4 gives White the upper hand on the queenside.}) 10. Ng5 $1 {There are two
important ideas behind this move: White threatens to win material with Qb3+
and also destroy opponent's pawn structure with Bxc6.} e6 ({After} 10... Kh8
11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Qb3 Qd6 13. Be3 $14 {Black has no enough counter-chances
because ...f5-f4 runs into Nge4!}) 11. Bxc6 bxc6 {This was Sandor,T - Karolyi,T
Hungary 1992 The consistent continuation would be} 12. Qb3 $146 Qd6 ({An equal
alternative is} 12... Re8 13. Nf3 a5 14. Be3 $14) 13. Nf3 Kh8 14. Be3 $14 {
with strong pressure on Black's double pawns.}) 9. e4 ({Another promising
option is} 9. a3 f5 10. Bd2 {, but after} f4 $1 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 Nd4 {
Black seems to have reasonable counterchances.}) 9... e5 {Black locks his
bishop, but strenghtens control of d4.} ({After} 9... f5 10. exf5 Bxf5 {
it makes sense for White to limit Black's counterattacking abilities by means
of} 11. h3 Nf6 12. Be3 Qd7 13. Kh2 e5 14. a3 $14 {with decent prospects on
queenside with b2-b4.}) ({After} 9... Bg4 10. h3 {it turns out, that h5-knight
is clearly misplaced.} Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nf6 12. Be3 e5 13. Bg2 $14 {A complex
struggle is ahead, when White maintains superior chances because his bishop
pair may become especially strong after ..f2-f4.}) 10. Bg5 $1 {this most
natural move is a novelty for some reason.} f6 {A committing move - but there
was no comfortable alternative.} ({After} 10... Bf6 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. h3 $14 {
White is ready to take the upper hand in the centre with d3-d4.}) ({Hardly
more attractive is} 10... Nf6 11. h3 h6 12. Be3 Nh7 13. Qd2 $14 {White reaches
an optimal setup with connected rooks and now can choose a proper moment for
..d3-d4 or f2-f4.}) 11. Be3 f5 {The h5-knight is stuck, so Black should play
this move.} 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. h3 {Threatening g3-g4.} Nf6 14. Qd2 {White's
forces are better mobilized for the upcoming struggle. A likely continuation is
} Qd7 15. g4 Be6 16. Ng5 {Exchanging the strong e6-bishop is White's undeniable
achievement.} Kh8 17. Nxe6 Qxe6 18. Rbe1 $14 {White will soon open the game
with f2-f4 in favor of bishop pair.} *

