1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 Nc6 7. d3 {This
position is very similar to KID tabia. Only the d3-pawn makes some difference,
and it gives its unique character.} h6 (7... a6 {Black goes for an interesting
ambitious plan with ...Rb8,b7-b5 as in one of main lines in KID.} 8. Rb1 {
White assumes, that ...b7-b5 will follow soon, so it makes sense to prevent
further expansion of opponent with b2-b4.} Rb8 9. b4 b5 ({The other moves are
less consistent:} 9... Bd7 10. a4 a5 {This move is a novelty, and I find it
very logical: Black secures b4 for his knight.} ({Too passive is} 10... Qc8 11.
b5 axb5 12. axb5 Ne5 {A sad necessity.} 13. Nxe5 dxe5 {This was Zoltek,T -
Wyrzykowski,J Zakopane 2008 It made sense to keep the tension by means of} 14.
Re1 $146 Bh3 15. Bh1 $14 {Black has no problems for his structural drawbacks.})
11. b5 Nb4 12. Ne1 {A multi-tasking move. White unblocks the f-pawn, so it
will be possible to initiate play on the queenside with f2-f4 and also intends
to exchange the knights after Ne1-c2.} c5 13. e4 e5 14. Nc2 $14 {White has
more space and the pieces are better coordinated.}) (9... e5 {is somewhat
inconsistent because it has no logical connection with Black's previous moves.}
10. b5 {The most straightforward.} axb5 11. cxb5 Ne7 12. a4 {White creates a
potentially strong passer.} h6 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Qc2 Be6 15. Rfc1 {White's
pressure on the c-file prevails.}) 10. cxb5 axb5 11. a4 $1 {It turns out that
White can develop initiative on the quuenside!} bxa4 12. b5 {Black lacks good
squares for the knight's retreat.} Na5 ({A serious concession is also} 12...
Ne5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Qxa4 Bb7 {This was Andersson,U - Laveryd,P Sweden 2000
Now the simple} 15. Be3 $146 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qd7 17. Rfc1 $16 {would have
offered White a huge positional advantage.}) 13. Qxa4 Ra8 {A brave decision.
Black reasonably doesn't fear of opposition on the long diagonal.} ({After}
13... Nb7 14. Nd4 Nc5 15. Qc2 $16 {White i firmly in a control in view of
..Nc6.}) 14. Qh4 $1 {Suddenly White switches to active measures on the opposite
side.} Bb7 15. Bh6 c5 16. Rfc1 $36 {Black still suffers from poor piece
coordination, and his king feels unsafe, especially in view of ..Ng5. Nowak,R -
Dubas,L Wisla 1998}) ({In case of} 7... Bd7 {White has few decent options, but
I mostly like the restricting} 8. h3 {, radically preventing Black from
exchanging fianchettoes bishop with ...Bh3.} a6 {This is another attempt to
make counterplay with ...b7-b5.} ({Too artificial is} 8... Qc8 9. Kh2 a6 (9...
e5 10. e4 Nh5 {was seen in Stelling,C - Schellmann,M Germany 2011 Now White
should have followed his general idea with} 11. Nd5 $146 {because} f5 $2 {
leads to fatal consequences:} 12. exf5 gxf5 13. Nxe5 $18) 10. e4 Rb8 11. Be3 $1
{A well-timed developing move.} b5 12. c5 e6 13. Rc1 $14 {Black has no
compensation for his space issues.}) 9. Be3 $5 {I like this flexible response.
White takes control over c1-h6 diagonal and vacates c1 for his rook.} ({
Another conceptual continuation is} 9. e4 $5 Rb8 10. d4 e5 11. d5 Ne7 {, but
it might suit KID players, although I still prefer White's chances.}) 9... Qc8
({After} 9... Rb8 10. Qd2 b5 11. Rac1 $14 {White has the more harmonious setup,
and ..Bh6 is to follow soon.}) 10. Kh2 h6 11. d4 $1 {it is a good moment for
traditional expansion in centre - most of Black's pieces are at back rank.} e5
12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Nd5 $14 {White has a slight, but long-lasting positional
advantage due to strong centralized d5-knight. Frois,A - Silva,M Vila Nova de
Gaia 2016}) (7... Bg4 {is a dubious idea because it practically means Black
will have to concess his bishop.} 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 e6 10. Bg2 Qd7 11. Bd2 $14
{Black was doomed to passive defence in Lafuente,P - Slipak,S Buenos Aires 2001
}) 8. Rb1 a5 (8... e5 {transposes to 6...e5 & Nc6.}) 9. b3 {This move mostly
fits out repertoire. There are few possible transpositions into other lines.} (
{The major line starts with} 9. a3 e5 10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 Be6 {, but this is
something I would like to avoid.}) 9... Bd7 {Among Black's possibilities this
is the most sensible developing move.} (9... e5 {transposes to 6...e5 & Nc6
with a7-a5.}) 10. Bb2 e5 {Black can hardly do without this advance for too
long.} ({The idea of exchanging the bishop with} 10... Qc8 11. e4 Bh3 {
shouldn't bother White:} 12. Nd5 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 e5 14. Rc1 $14 {The exchange on
d5 isn't acceptable for Black in any situation, so White keeps pressure.}) 11.
Qd2 $146 {I like this natural idea: White connects his rooks and invites his
opponent to show his cards.} ({The only preceding correspondence game saw} 11.
a3 Re8 12. e3 Qc8 13. Nd2 Bh3 {Black was fine in Herriot,B - Dzenis,J ICCF
email 2012}) 11... Re8 ({In the event of} 11... Nh7 12. e3 f5 {White manages
to prevent further extension of opponent by means of} 13. Nh4 $1 Qe8 14. f4 g5
15. Nf3 $14 {Black's position is rather unpleasant in view of ..Nc3-d5. The
poor h7-knight is gonna stay out of play.}) 12. e4 {white stabilizes situation
in the centre and secures d5 for his knight.} Nh7 {Black moves his knight
towards d4. Hardly, he intends to play ...f7-f5 after moving his king's rook.}
13. Ne2 {White takes more control of d4.} Ng5 14. Ne1 $1 {An ambitious
concept: White avoids unnecessary simplifications and signals that he wants to
play f2-f4.} Ne6 15. f4 Ncd4 {The knight reached its destination, but it took
a long time.} (15... Ned4 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 {leads to the same.}) 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17.
Qf2 $14 {White has decent prospects on the kingside, while Black's counterplay
is questionable.} *

