1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 e5 7. d3 Nbd7 {
This is Black's 3rd choice on practice. Like in Classical KID with g3, Black
temporarily blocks his light-squared bishop, when his knight is heading on c5
in most cases.} 8. b4 {Quite a rare, but rather ambitious continuation. Like
in English opening or ''reversed closed Sicilian,'' White starts extending on
the queenside, and now it is tougher for Black to restrict the fianchettoed Bg2
with c7-c6.} a5 {The most consistent continuation - by provoking b4-b5 Black
secures c5 for his knight.} ({The attempt to take advantage of opposition on
the long diagonal with} 8... e4 $2 9. dxe4 Nxe4 {fails to} 10. Nxe4 Bxa1 11.
Bg5 Bf6 (11... f6 {is equally bad because after} 12. Bh6 Be5 13. Bxf8 Qxf8 14.
Nxe5 dxe5 15. c5 $18 {Black is unable to complete his development.}) 12. Nxf6+
Nxf6 13. Qd4 Kg7 14. Qh4 Re8 {This position occurred in Jere,D - Tafira,T
Boksburg 2016 Here the simple} 15. Nd4 $1 $146 Qe7 16. Rd1 $18 {would have put
Black in a hopeless situation in view of the fatal pin.}) (8... Re8 {is a
double-edged decision - in case Black doesn't manage to push either d6-d5 or
e5-e4 this move turns a loss of tempo. Also, it diminishes the effect of f7-f5.
} 9. e4 {This time White blocks his fianchettoed bishop to reach stability in
the centre and heavily limits the opponent's activity.} a5 {Black secures c5
for his knight, but allows White to grab lots of space.} ({The other plan is}
9... c6 10. a4 d5 11. cxd5 cxd5 {In case of exd5, Black can regain the pawn in
favorable redaction with ...Nb6. We have been following the game Micheli,C
-Turikov,V Dresden 2010 Here I like the following approach:} 12. a5 $146 d4 13.
Nb5 Nf8 14. Na3 $1 $14 {White's pieces are better coordinated for upcoming
positional struggle. Black faces difficulties with covering e5.}) 10. b5 Nc5
11. h3 {A decent prophylactic move. White secures e3 for his bishop and
prevents the possible ...Bg4.} c6 ({Artificial is} 11... Nh5 {Di Stefano,M -
Nikolic,S Zuerich 1988} 12. Be3 b6 13. Qc2 Bb7 14. Rad1 $14 {Black is doomed
to passive defense, and the h5-knight is clearly misplaced.}) ({The immediate}
11... Nfd7 {is nicely met by} 12. Bg5 $1 f6 13. Be3 $14 {Black lacks space,
and the g7-bishop is out of play.}) 12. Rb1 Nfd7 13. Be3 {Instead, 13.Bg5
wasn't as effective as before because of Qc7.} Ne6 14. Kh2 {A decent
prophylactic move. Moving the king might potentially make f2-f4 more effective.
} Ndc5 {Black has reached an optimal setup for his knights, but it took a long
time.} ({After} 14... Nd4 15. Ne2 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 {White is ready to initiative
active play with f2-f4, while Black's counterplay is questionable. For
instance,} Nc5 17. Bg2 Bd7 18. f4 $14) 15. d4 {A well-timed break.} exd4 16.
Nxd4 $14 {Black has no compensation for lack of space and weak d6-pawn.}) (8...
Ne8 {to push f7-f5 is a standard KID approach, but Black's pieces are not
well-coordinated here.} 9. Rb1 f5 10. c5 $1 {As usual, White aims to open the
game before the opponent consolidates.} h6 {Of course, 10...e4 11.dxe4 is bad
for Black because of 11...Bxc3 12.Qb3+.} 11. cxd6 cxd6 12. e4 Ndf6 {This
position occured in Grosse Kloenne,E - Reinke,M Germany 1994 Now White could
have claimed superiority by means of} 13. Nh4 $146 Kh7 14. exf5 gxf5 15. f4 $16
{Black's pieces are cramped, and he suffers from weak f5-pawn.}) 9. b5 Nc5 {
This position took place in a couple of games. Among White's interesting
possibilities, I mostly like} 10. Nd2 $146 {White transfers his knight to b3,
to neutralize Black's most active piece.} h5 {This is the most ambitious
attempt to make counterplay on the kingside.} ({After} 10... Rb8 11. Nb3 b6 12.
Nxc5 dxc5 13. Bb2 $14 {Black has no compensation for his structural drawbacks.}
) 11. h4 {White radically prevents ..h5-h4 at cost of weakening g4. On the
other hand, g5 belongs to White's knight either.} Ng4 12. Nde4 ({Much weaker is
} 12. Nb3 $6 Ne6 $1 {, and then Black manages to develop his play with
...f5-f4,g6-g5 and so on.}) 12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 f5 {Black hardly can make any
significant counterplay without advancing the f-pawn.} 14. Ng5 f4 15. e3 $14 {
White has the better chances due to full control over long diagonal.} *

