1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 {This move was
played by many strong players. In most cases Black opts for...e7-e5 next and
it leads to other Chapters, but there are some exceptions.} 7. d3 a5 {A
flexible choice. Black makes it tougher for White to play b2-b4 and keeps the
options of switching to usual KID paths with ...e7-e5.} (7... e5 {transposes to
6...e5 & Nbd7.}) ({The attempt to initiate some active play with b7-b5 isn't
too realistic:} 7... a6 8. Rb1 c6 ({In the event of} 8... Rb8 9. b4 b5 10. Nd4
$1 $36 {the weak c6-spot causes Black serious problems.}) 9. b4 e5 10. e4 b5
11. a4 $14 {White was much more active in Jund,C-Provang,B France 1994}) ({
Another idea is to stabilize situation on the q-side by means of} 7... c5 8.
Rb1 Rb8 9. b4 b6 {, as in Dardha,D - Domingo Nunez,R Chess.com INT 2023 Now
White could have put Black under strong pressure on the queenside with} 10. Qa4
$146 a6 11. bxc5 Nxc5 12. Qa3 $14) 8. h3 $5 {White reacts in a tricky way
either. After this universal prophylactic move Black is invited to show his
cards.} ({The most common alternative plan is} 8. Rb1 e5 9. a3 c6 10. b4 axb4
11. axb4 {, but after} d5 $1 {Black doesn't seem to have serious problems: his
powerful centre compensates for some issues with c8-bishop.}) 8... e5 {Hardly
Black can do without this advance for too long.} ({After} 8... Nc5 9. e4 {
Black has nothing better than} e5 {, with transposition.}) 9. e4 {White blocks
his fianchettoed bishop, but heavily limits opponent's active possibilities.}
Nc5 ({After} 9... c6 {White can play} 10. Rb1 {, that takes the game to
Chapter with 6...c6 7.d3 a5.} (10. Be3 $5 {is another decent option.})) 10. Be3
{Vulnerability of c7-knight causes Black definite difficulties. In particular,
White can capture e5 in various redactions.} Ne6 ({In the event of} 10... Nfd7
11. d4 exd4 12. Bxd4 $14 {White grabs lots of space and neutralizes opponent's
important fianchettoed bishop.}) 11. d4 Nd7 $1 {This is the most challenging
move for White - Black is maintaining the tension and declares his intention
to play ...f7-f5 anytime soon.} ({After} 11... exd4 12. Nxd4 Re8 13. Re1 $14 {
Black desperately lacked space in Gvetadze,S - Agrest,I Plovdiv 2014}) 12. d5
$146 {The only way to fight for initiative. The current position is typical for
KID.} ({Worse is} 12. Qd2 {Barbosa,R - Morioka,F Araraquara 2023 in view of}
exd4 $146 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Ne5 15. b3 c5 $132 {, and then White is
forced to capture e5 because} 16. Be3 $6 Bxh3 $1 {loses a pawn.}) 12... Nec5
13. Qc2 f5 {Hardly this counter-attacking action should be delayed.} ({
In case Black is trying to choose a more comfortable redaction and plays} 13...
h6 {White can also effectively regroup his forces with} 14. Kh2 $1 f5 15. exf5
gxf5 16. Nh4 e4 17. Ng6 Re8 18. Rad1 $36 {the upcoming f2-f3 break will be
unpleasant for Black, whose queenside pieces are undeveloped.}) 14. exf5 gxf5
15. Ng5 {White unblocks his f-pawn, while the knight is heading on e6.} Nf6 ({
In the event of} 15... Nb6 16. b3 h6 17. Ne6 {the b6-knight turns misplaced. A
likely continuation is} Nxe6 18. dxe6 Bxe6 19. Bxb6 cxb6 20. Bxb7 Ra7 21. Bd5
$14 {Superiority of c3-knight over Black's bishop is obvious.}) 16. Rae1 {
The main struggle will be held on the kingside, so White makes last
preparations.} h6 ({The immediate} 16... e4 {can be well met by} 17. Ne2 $1 h6
18. Bxc5 dxc5 ({An equal possibility is} 18... hxg5 19. Bd4 Bd7 20. f3 $36) 19.
Ne6 Bxe6 20. dxe6 $14 {White is ready to support his strong passer with Ne2-f4.
}) 17. Nf3 e4 {The most aggressive choice. Black secures d3 for the knight.} ({
After} 17... b6 18. Kh2 Bd7 19. Nh4 f4 20. Bxc5 bxc5 21. Ne4 $14 {White takes
control over light squares, and Black's counterplay is neutralized.}) 18. Nh4
Nd3 19. Rd1 $1 {A precise move. Keeping an option of ..Rxd3 in the long run is
important.} Nh5 ({After} 19... Ne5 20. Qe2 Bd7 21. Nb5 $14 {Black's
counterplay is limited, while White's main idea is to undermine the centre with
f2-f3.}) 20. Rxd3 $1 {A well-timed exchange sacrifice. It is crucial to prevent
...f5-f4.} exd3 21. Qd1 $1 {By playing this intermediate move White invites
interesting complications.} ({Weaker is} 21. Qxd3 f4 {, and Black is fine.})
21... f4 22. Bd2 Qe8 23. g4 f3 $1 {The best try. Black vacates f4 for his
knight.} ({After} 23... Nf6 24. Re1 Qf7 25. Nb5 $1 {White is firmly in a
control due to excellent piece coordination.}) 24. Bxf3 Nf4 25. Bxf4 Rxf4 26.
Qxd3 $44 {Activity of pieces and control over light squares provide White
