Nc5 13. b4 Ne6 14. h4 $1 {A decent move. White is ready to activate his
light-squared bishop by means of Bg2-h3.} a5 (14... Nd4 15. Qd1 Qd7 16. Be3 $14
{Black has to do with a strategic threat of ..Bxd4, followed by f2-f4.}) 15. b5
Nd7 16. Ne2 Ndc5 17. Bh3 $14 {Black's counterplay is questionable, whereas
White has few interesting ideas such as Kg2,Rh1, h5 or Ba3, followed by Bxe6
at some point.}) (9... h6 {This move is mainly aimed for securing e6 for
c8-bishop, although it is still not an optimal spot.} 10. Re1 Be6 {This was
Franciskovic,B - L'Ami,A Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 Here I suggest} 11. h3 $146 Nbd7
12. b3 {White strenthens c4 to occupy the centre with d3-d4.} c5 13. b4 b6 14.
Be3 $14 {White has more space and better piece coordination because the
d7-knight is inferior to c3-knight.}) (9... a5 {trasnposes to 8...a5.}) 10. b4
{White grabs some space and deprives the d7-knight of c5.} a6 {This was played
by great Vishy Anand. Black signals that he wants to play ...b7-b5 at some
point.} ({The alternatives are:} 10... a5 11. b5 Nc5 12. Be3 Bg4 {This
position took place in the correspondence game Wrba K - Backlund B ICCF 1996
Now the most flexible seems} 13. Qc2 $5 {avoiding the pin and connecting the
rooks.} Ne6 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nd7 {Black builds his counterplay on d4 and c5
outpost for his knights.} 16. Ne2 Ndc5 17. Bg2 $14 {Black lacks any
constructive ideas despite the strong knights and can only sit and wait. White
will try to develop his play with f2-f4 or d3-d4 at proper moment.}) ({Risky is
} 10... d5 {Abdulaziz,M - Safin,S Bled 2002 Black's pieces are not fully
mobilized, and White can now seize the initiative by means of} 11. exd5 $1 cxd5
12. Re1 d4 ({After} 12... dxc4 13. dxc4 h6 14. Bb2 $14 {Black struggles to
complete development of queenside pieces.}) 13. Nb5 Bf8 14. c5 $36 {White's
play on the queenside is lasting itself.}) (10... Nf8 {For some reason, this
is Black's top choice. I believe Black will hardly benefit from placing his
knight on e6.} 11. h3 Ne6 12. Be3 Nd7 {This was Batyte,D - Newrkla,K Austria
2020 White has many decent options here, when I prefer} 13. Qd2 $146 a5 14. b5
Ndc5 15. d4 $1 {White is perfectly ready for this thematic advance.} exd4 16.
Nxd4 $14 {Black suffers from weak d6-pawn.}) 11. h3 {White reasonably ignores
opponent's last move, and continues his general idea.} Nf8 ({After} 11... b5 12.
a4 $1 Rb8 13. Be3 $14 {Black's position feels rather crumped mainly because of
c8-bishop.}) 12. Be3 Ne6 13. Qd2 {Reaching an optimal setup.} Nd7 14. Kh2 {
A decent move. White moves his king away of possible checks on g1-a7 diagonal
in advance and invites Black to show his cards.} Qe7 {The natural play by both
sides led to this position in Andersson,U - Anand,V Monte Carlo 1997 Now I
like the following ambitious idea:} 15. Ng1 $1 $146 Nd4 16. f4 {White can do
with an active d4 because Black's other pieces are poorly coordinated. It is
time to start actions on the kingside.} exf4 17. gxf4 f5 18. Rbe1 $36 {White
has the better prospects in the upcoming complex struggle.} *

