1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 e5 7. d3 c6 8. Rb1 a5
{A top choice by Black. As after 7...Nc6 8.Rb1 a5, Black makes it tougher for
the opponent to extend on the q-side. In the case of 9.a3, followed by b2-b4,
Black will get control over the open a-file and also get rid of a-pawn that
sometimes becomes rather vulnerable.} 9. h3 $5 {Quite a rare move. White
deprives the opponent's minor pieces of g4 and secures e3 for his dark-squared
bishop.} Nbd7 {Hardly Black can benefit from delaying this developing move.} (
9... h6 {This move is connected with approximately same ideas as h2-h3.} 10. e4
Re8 ({In the event of} 10... Be6 11. Be3 Nbd7 12. b3 Qe7 13. d4 {it turns out,
that e6-bishop is misplaced and White obtains a favorable version of KID with
g2-g3, when Black's counterplay is limited. Kemp,P - Craig,T ICCF email 2003})
11. b3 ({In case of} 11. Re1 Na6 12. Be3 Be6 {Black keeps an eye on c4, so
d3-d4 isn't coming yet. At the same time, Black is ready for ...d6-d5.}) (11.
d4 {takes the game to KID paths. I believe, this redaction is acceptable for
White, but still text is more flexible.}) 11... Nbd7 ({Black's pieces are still
undeveloped, so} 11... d5 {is premature:} 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Re1 d4 14. Nb5 Nc6
15. Ba3 $36 {White takes the upper hand on the queenside.}) 12. Be3 {White has
reached his harmonious setup, while the opponent's bishop is still on c8.} Rb8
13. Qd2 Kh7 14. a3 $14 {White neutralizes Black's only active ideas, as} b5 15.
cxb5 cxb5 16. b4 {puts Black under strong pressure on the b-file.}) ({The
ambitious} 9... Nh5 {with an obvious intention to play f7-f5 , as in
Nugumanov,B - Aitbayev,A Almaty 2007 turns insufficient in view of} 10. e4 $146
f5 $6 {A dubious move, but this is the only way to justify 10...Nh5.} 11. exf5
gxf5 12. Nxe5 {A standard tactical shot: the h5-knight is hanging.} Nxg3 13.
Nxc6 Nxc6 14. fxg3 $16 {Black has no compensation for the pawn.}) (9... Re8 {
has no independent value as after} 10. e4 {both} Nbd7 {are transposiitons.} ({
and} 10... h6)) 10. e4 {This important position might be reached with
different move orders.} Nc5 {It is time to activate the knight and unblock the
light-squared bishop.} (10... Re8 11. Be3 Nc5 {is another possible moves order.
}) 11. Be3 Re8 {We have been following the game Kovalev,D - Demchenko,A
Chess.com INT 2020} ({After} 11... Qe7 12. Re1 Re8 13. Qd2 {the e7-queen isn't
placed optimally, and it can be illustrated in the following line:} Bd7 14.
Rbd1 b5 {the only active try.} 15. cxb5 cxb5 16. Bg5 $1 {The pin is annoying,
and ..Nc3-d5 will follow soon.}) {Here I suggest} 12. Re1 $146 {White is
getting ready for ..d3-d4.} a4 {A standard approach in that type of position:
Black grabs some space and vacates a5 for his queen.} ({In the event of} 12...
Be6 13. Nxe5 $1 {the tactical complications are favorable for White:} Nfxe4 14.
Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Nxf7 Bxf7 16. Bxe4 $16) 13. Qc2 Qa5 ({After} 13... Bd7 14. b4 $1
{White manages to quickly extend and deprive opponent's knight of c5:} axb3 15.
axb3 Ne6 16. b4 Qc7 17. c5 $14 {Black's position is very cramped.}) 14. b4 {
eventually, White makes use of b1-rook!} axb3 15. axb3 Qb4 {This attempt to
block the b-pawn isn't effective.} 16. Bd2 Qb6 17. b4 Ne6 18. Ra1 $1 {White
can afford to leave the b4-pawn uncovered because after 18...Rxa1 19.Rxa1 Qxb4?
20.Na4 Black loses his queen.} Bd7 19. Na4 Qc7 20. c5 $14 {White has a
traditional space advantage, and the knight is ready for landing on b6.} *

