1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 c6 {A flexible move.
By playing this Black invites his opponent to enter KID with 7.d4, but this is
another topic.} 7. d3 d5 {This move is rare, but definitely challenging for
White: Black interrupts White's original plans as now e2-e4 advance is
neutralized or at least delayed.} 8. Be3 $5 {An original way of maintaining the
tension. Whote blocks his e-pawn, but takes control of d4 and connects the
rooks.} ({After} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. d4 {the game transposes to one of Gruenfeld
lines that is currently considered harmless.}) 8... Ng4 {This move hasn't been
played, but I find it very natural: Black unblocks his g7-bishop with a tempo.}
({The attempt to simplify the matters with} 8... dxc4 $146 9. dxc4 Nbd7 {
doesn't offer Black full equality because he has issues with activating
c8-bishop.} ({After} 9... Qxd1 10. Rfxd1 Na6 11. h3 $14 {White is much more
active.}) {For instance,} 10. h3 {Eliminating both ...Bg4 and Ng4.} Qa5 11. Rc1
Rd8 12. Qa4 $1 Qxa4 13. Nxa4 $14 {White has a slight, but long-lasting
advantage because of superior piece coordination and pressure on a7.}) (8...
Bg4 {This move is somewhat risky as it weakens b7 but Black lacks good
squares for his bishop anyway.} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 (9... cxd5 10. Qb3 $14) 10. Bd2
Qd7 {This position was seen in Reina Figueredo,A-Rodriguez Alas,B Camaguey 2010
Here I suggest the following way to regroup the pieces:} 11. Qc1 $5 $146 e5 12.
Bh6 Re8 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Rd1 {White has the more pleasant play. He has
superior piece coordination, and it should tell after he plays d3-d4 at some
point.}) ({The ambitious} 8... e5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 ({After} 9... cxd5 10. Bg5 h6
11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Qb3 $14 {White's fianchettoed bishop becomes very strong,
and Black struggles to cover his central pawns without making concessions.}) {
is well met by} 10. Bg5 $1 {White interrupts Black's natural development.} Qa5
({After} 10... f6 11. Bd2 Be6 12. a3 a5 {, as in Stohl,I - Oral,T Olomouc 1998
White can claim his superior piece coordination by means of} 13. Qc2 $1 $146
Nd7 14. d4 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 $14) 11. Bd2 Qd8 12. Qb3 {White connects his rooks
and makes it tougher for opponent to develop his queenside pieces.} Nb6 13. a4
Be6 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Anand,V - Boro ICC
INT 2007 Here I mostly like} 14. Qa3 $146 a5 15. Ng5 Bf5 16. Nge4 $14 {White
can host his knight on d6 or c5. Black struggles to harmoniously spot his minor
pieces.}) 9. Bd2 dxc4 ({After} 9... d4 10. Na4 Na6 11. b4 $14 {White takes the
upper hand on the queenside and}) 10. dxc4 Nd7 11. h3 Nge5 {The knight's trade
definitely should suit Black, who has a bit less space.} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. b3
$14 {Black struggles to find a decent square for his c8-bishop, while White is
ready to advance his e and f pawns to start ''squeezing'' Black.} *

