1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 c6 {A tricky idea.
From now White has to do with ...d6-d5 advance that heavily limits White's
actions in the centre. On the other hand, it blocks the b8-knight and makes it
easier for White to open the b-file after ..b2-b4-b5.} 7. d3 a6 {A flexible
move that many strong grandmasters played. Black not only diminishes the
effect of ..b4-b5 but also signals that he can initiate play on the queenside
with ...b7-b5 at the proper moment.} (7... Qa5 {Like in KID with 6...c6, this
ambitious move is connected with two ideas: Black can either opt for ...b7-b5
break or transfer his queen to h5 in order to put some pressure on White's
king.} 8. Rb1 {I see no reason for deviating from this tempting move: White
will play b2-b4 with a tempo.} Qh5 9. b4 Bh3 {This is consistent, but the
bishop's trade shouldn't bother White, whose king remains safe.} 10. b5 Nbd7
11. Ng5 $1 {White forces an exchange in favorable redaction to release
pressure on h2.} Bxg2 12. Kxg2 h6 13. Nf3 d5 ({Also after} 13... c5 14. e4 e6
15. Ne2 g5 16. h4 $1 {Black's main issue is mispalced h5-queen.}) 14. bxc6 bxc6
15. cxd5 cxd5 16. h3 $14 {The poor h5-queen is in trouble, and White has
plenty of play along the b-file.}) (7... Nbd7 {mostly doesn't have an
independent value} 8. Rb1 a5 ({After} 8... e5 9. b4 d5 10. Nd2 $1 {White's
fianchettoed bishop becomes exceptionally effective} d4 11. Nce4 Ne8 ({Hardly
better is} 11... Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Qc7 13. b5 $36) 12. Nb3 f5 {This was Manouck,T -
Apicella,M Cannes 1994 Now the most natural} 13. Ng5 $146 Nc7 14. a4 h6 15. Nf3
$14 {would have put Black in an unpleasant situation - his queenside pieces are
cramped, and ..e2-e3 will follow at any moment.}) 9. e4 e5 10. h3 {leads to
positions from}) 8. Rb1 {It is important to choose a proper moment for pushing
b2-b4.} ({Premature is} 8. b4 d5 $1 9. Bb2 dxc4 10. dxc4 Be6 $132 {Black has
excellent play against c4.}) 8... b5 {A critical continuation. Black doesn't
fear dangerous opposition on the long diagonal.} (8... d5 {makes a strange
impression because Black previously played d7-d6 and a7-a6. On the other hand,
Black is trying to prove that Ra1-b1 was rather slow as well.} 9. Qb3 $1 {
At his turn, White claims the main drawback of a7-a6: weak b6-spot in Black's
camp.} Re8 ({After} 9... d4 10. Na4 Nfd7 11. c5 $36 {Black's queenside pieces
very cramped in Heberla,B - Jasny,S Czech Republic 2009}) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Bf4
Nc6 12. Rbc1 $14 {In case of 12...e5 13.Bg5 Black will face problems with
covering d5. At the same time, White is ready to extend his initiative on the
c-file with 13.Ne5.}) 9. Nd4 $1 {The most energetic response.} d5 {The most
radical solution, although it weakens c5.} ({After} 9... Bb7 10. cxb5 axb5 11.
Ndxb5 $14 {Black doesn't have sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) ({
Too akward is} 9... Qb6 10. Be3 Qb7 11. Nb3 $14) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. a3 Bb7 $146
{A solid choice.} ({The more active} 11... e5 12. Nb3 Nc6 13. Bg5 $14 {was
problematic for Black in view of weak d5-pawn in Anastasian,A-Tal,M Yerevan
1986}) 12. Nb3 {White takes control of key dark squares c5 & a5.} Nbd7 13. Bd2
Rc8 ({Approximately the same type of position emerges after} 13... e6 14. Rc1
Rc8 15. Na2 $14) 14. Na2 $1 {A decent manoevre. White's minor pieces are
placed harmoniously now.} Qb6 15. Ba5 Qa7 16. e3 {White has a slight but
stable positional advantage due to control over Black squares and passive
b7-bishop.} *

